</taxonomicName>
group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="344" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1771,2013]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
Externally, species are characterized by dark markings (a spot or fascia) on the costal margin of the forewing; a frontal tuft that is pure white to golden cream or dull yellow (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[844,967,1807,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="myxodes">
<emphasis box="[844,967,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. myxodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), or orange-ochre (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[1186,1348,1807,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subviolacea">
<emphasis box="[1186,1348,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. subviolacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). In the male genitalia, the uncus possesses two slender, short or long lateral lobes; the gnathos is a large plate with a distinctive, wide, spiny caudal process; and the vinculum has a distinctive, long, rod-like juxta (
<figureCitation box="[1197,1263,1879,1905]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). In the female genitalia, apophyses are long; anal papillae are modified into a single, round, oval or triangular element (
<figureCitation box="[1310,1374,1915,1941]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) (see Discussion); the signum is absent (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[544,668,1951,1977]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="myxodes">
<emphasis box="[544,668,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. myxodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), weakly developed, indistinctive (
<taxonomicName box="[1064,1238,1951,1977]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subviolaceae">
<emphasis box="[1064,1238,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. subviolaceae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[1253,1389,1951,1977]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similantis">
<emphasis box="[1253,1389,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. similantis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), or well-developed, lamellar (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[446,549,1987,2013]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="frigida">
<emphasis box="[446,549,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">P. frigida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="345" startId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" targetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" targetPageId="4">
